default1.2
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultOral evidence was given to the Home Affairs Select Committee by Sir Graham Bright, Tony Lloyd and Ron Ball on the 26
defaultth
default November 2013.
default&#xa0;
default1.3
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultPCCs can maintain and increase public confidence in policing. PCCs are working hard to ensure local communities have a stronger voice in policing. Working with Chief Constables PCCS are transforming the way forces interact with the public so that policing in the 21
defaultst
default century is more responsive to communities’ concerns about crime.
default&#xa0;default2.1
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe Association of Police and Crime Commissioners (APCC) is a company limited by guarantee. The APCC services are overseen and directed by PCCs. 
default&#xa0;default3.1
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultA key role for PCCs is to ensure that the public and victims have a stronger voice in policing. PCCs’ policing and crime plans demonstrate how they are doing this, by putting local community and victims needs at the heart of their vision.
default As a result of consultation policing and crime plans reflect the views and interests of the communities they represent.
default3.2
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultKeeping crime low is central to public confidence in policing and PCCs remain vigilant about reducing crime and holding their forces to account to ensure this happens in practice.
default However, it’s important to note that reducing crime isn’t about the police alone.
default&#xa0;
default3.3
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultOver the next year PCCs will be taking on much wider responsibilities for local criminal justice matters, i.e. wider commissioning of services.  This will play an increasingly important role in how PCCs reduce crime and deliver an effective 
defaultcriminal justice 
defaultservice
default, including policing
default.
default&#xa0;
default3.4
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultCrime has continued to fall since PCCs came into office, down 5-7% on the previous year and is now at record low levels with a national decline in reduction of violent crime.
default There is some evidence of a nascent increase in some forms of crime, for example shoplifting and theft from the person. There is also an increase in sexual offences in some areas although this has been
default attributed to a rise in reporting historic crimes.
default 
defaultI
defaultt’s important to note that a comparison of pre-PCC and post-PCC crime statistics will not be available until early 2014.
default3.5
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultAlthough it is still early in the piece to judge overall effectiveness there are already plenty of examples of PCCs
default, both individually and collectively,
default demonstrating their ability to effect positive change in reducing crime and delivering an effective police service.
default&#xa0;
