default5.6
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIn conclusion PCCS believe that PCPS are well placed to scrutinise the delivery of their functions and that as they mature they are increasingly making full use of their existing powers.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;default6.1
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe 
defaultunderlying intention of Stage 2 is that operational staff under the control and direction of Chief Constables will pass to their employment.
default 
defaultPCCs retain responsibility for the budget and holding forces to account. 
default&#xa0;
default6.2
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultNo one force’s Stage 2 plan is exactly the same as another.  There are variations in what each PCC proposes, 
defaultwith
default some keeping a larger number of staff than others and some keeping functions which others are not.  PCCs and chief constables are 
defaultdeciding
default locally 
defaultwhat is best for their forces, ultimately to reduce crime and deliver an effective police service.
default&#xa0;
default6.3
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultAlthough all Stage 2 plans are different it is possible to say that most plans will see the majority of police staff transferring to the employment of the Chief Constable, whilst the PCC will continue to employ a small body of support staff to help run their offices and support them in their oversight and scrutiny functions. 
default&#xa0;
default6.4
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultAll 
defaultplans
default are still subject to the approval of the Home Secretary and we expect confirmation of plans from December, in time for implementation in April 2014.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;default7.1
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultCommissioners have maintained progress on working with chief constables to bring down the cost of policing in line with the government's targets, without so far a significant adverse impact on performance and crime levels. This has been achieved through efficiency and capacity enhancements, reductions in bureaucracy, and more robust scrutiny and challenge. 
defaultBut it would be wrong to suggest that austerity has not posed a significant challenge for leaders of the police service.
default&#xa0;
default7.2
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIt should be noted that HMIC has identified an increased number of forces where further reductions may risk services delivered to the public.
default&#xa0;
default7.3
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWhile
default significant success has been achieved through collaboration, better procurement, and more efficient use of staff resources, looking ahead, substantial further grant reductions are likely.
default 
defaultThe scope to cut costs is not infinite, and Commissioners 
defaultneed
default the government to work with them to consider the long term configuration of services and resourcing levels which will ensure that services remain sustainable. There is also a need to consider better approaches to the management of demands for policing and community services.
default&#xa0;
default7.4
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIn year 1, 
defaultthe vast majority of 
defaultCommissioners have set precepts which have been at or
default 
defaultbelow the government's threshold. While recognising the need to control local taxation levels, PCCs were elected on the basis of clear statements about local plans and priorities. There is a powerful case for arguing that the stringent controls on 
defaultprecept
default increases should be relaxed where the increase is linked to delivering additional services requested by communities. 
default&#xa0;
default7.5
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultUltimately, PCCs are responsible for the safety of their communities. As the austerity 
defaultagenda 
defaultcontinue
defaults
default, there may come a point in some areas where the Force is unable to sustain current levels of services and expectations within 
defaultthe
default resources available from grant and the target level of Council Tax.  PCCs will be monitoring performance locally, and this could trigger the need for increases in Council Tax above the 
defaultthreshold.
default&#xa0;
default7.6
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultShould any Commissioner wish to raise the precept above the stated threshold they would need licence from their 
defaultcommunities
default (via a referendum) and they would need to consider the cost implications of such a course of action.
default&#xa0;
default7.7
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultA number of Commissioners have cited concerns about further impacts on their budgets:
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default7.8
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultCommissioners can only deliver through others. In the case of the chief, the PCC can set targets and hold the Force to account. It is not the same with other partners who, by their own actions, can impact on Policing resources. A prime example is in relation to Health, where changes to the way Mental Health care is commissioned, and pressures on Ambulance Services can impact on policing. In situations where an individual is in crisis, such as those placed under Section 136 of the Mental Health Act 1983 and may represent a danger to themselves or others, too often the police service is expected to act as 'last resort' with insufficient support from the health and social care partners who are better placed to deal with the needs of the individual.  PCCs need the power to apply policy or financial levers on these partner services in such circumstances, or there should be a transfer of resources nationally.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;default8.1
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThis is one of the areas where PCCs have been able to demonstrate a clear difference over the system that preceded them. PCCs are more engaged and better recognised by their local communities. They communicate and consult more with the local community and as such their agenda better reflects the priorities of local people. Whilst only 7% of the public were aware that they could go to their police authority if they were unhappy with their policing (Cabinet Office Research 2007), a ComRes poll for the BBC revealed that 62% of the public are aware of the work of PCCs.
default PCCs are achieving this greater recognition as a result of the level of engagement with their communities. 
default&#xa0;
default8.2
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultPCCs can demonstrate substantial engagement with their local communities. The Staffordshire PCC for example has engaged face to face with over 12,000 people in Staffordshire since 1 January 2013.
default&#xa0;
default8.3
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultPCCs are 
defaultprogressing good work to promote their local policing priorities. 
defaultBelow 
defaultprovides a summary of the most often mentioned PCC’s individual key priorities in police and crime plans:
