default&#xa0;default9.1
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultCollaboration is one of a number of areas of focus, and experience shows that collaboration projects are often a big commitment of resources while they are being planned, and often take time to produce real benefits. Many forces are focusing on ensuring that they are as efficient as possible before undertaking more ambitious collaboration projects.
default&#xa0;
default9.2
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultPCCs are collaborating well with other PCCs. In the South West for example PCCs meet every six weeks and have already approved three collaborative ventures. 
default&#xa0;
default9.3
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWhilst fully recognising the value of collaboration, Commissioners are focused on the here and now, and the really big savings on budgets at this time still come from reducing directly employed staff levels, and increasing the efficiency of those that remain.
default&#xa0;
default9.4
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultAlthough focussed on the here and now there are great examples of PCCs reaping the benefits of sharing resources with different agencies. 
defaultFor example, t
defaulthe co-location of services where
default 
defaultpolice, council and health workers are all based in the same building
default generates
default modest financial benefits 
defaultbut also 
defaulthas a much more fundamental benefit of getting agencies to work better in partnership which feeds into the strategic overview of reducing crime and reducing demand.
